    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-05-09T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-05-09T07:00:00-05:00" n="135"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d135">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 GE/5–954: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">United States Delegation</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret<lb/>priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-05-09T13:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 9, 1954—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 156. Sent priority Seoul 60, repeated
                    information priority Tokyo 38. Tokyo for <gloss target="#t_CINCFE1"
                        >CINCFE</gloss>. Comments re <gloss target="#t_Tosec1">Tosec</gloss> 107,
                    repeated Seoul 902<note n="1" xml:id="d135fn1">Dated May 8, <ref
                            target="#pg_234">p. 234</ref>.</note> and Seoul’s 59<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d135fn2">Same as telegram 1134, May 8, from Seoul, <ref
                            target="#pg_226">p. 226</ref>.</note> and 62 to Geneva:<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d135fn3">Dated May 8, <ref target="#pg_233">p. 233</ref>.</note>
                    <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Delegation Geneva considers entirely unlikely allies accept proposal
                            for surrender North Korea Army to <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>
                            and in effect automatic extension <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>
                            sovereignty over North Korea. US would be put in ridiculous untenable
                            position to suggest or support such proposal.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Paragraph 1, <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 149, repeated
                            Seoul 58<note n="4" xml:id="d135fn4">Dated May 8, <ref target="#pg_230"
                                    >p. 230</ref>.</note> gives delegation’s views on proposal
                                <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 57.<note n="5"
                                xml:id="d135fn5">The reference is apparently incorrect; it should be
                                to telegram <gloss target="#t_Tosec1">Tosec</gloss> 97, May 7, to
                                Geneva, <ref target="#pg_224">p. 224</ref>.</note> Delegation
                            suggests question now is have we reached this last resort and when
                            should we proceed develop plan B with other 14 and without <gloss
                                target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> if, as seems probable, <persName
                                corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> insists on impossible terms.
                            Believe unrealistic assume <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> can be
                            persuaded or expected remain silent. They will probably take stand along
                            lines <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>’s views, as <persName
                                corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName> was about to do in plenary last
                                Monday.<note n="6" xml:id="d135fn6">May 3.</note> This alternative
                            means (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) we reverse our policy of US-<gloss
                                target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> collaboration, but we see no
                            alternative if <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> adheres
                            extreme, unrealistic views and if <persName corresp="#p_PYT1"
                                >Pyun</persName> is deceiving or completely misleading us here re
                            plan B, and (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                                >Rhee</persName> will end up as appearing be cause for failure of
                            conference, not Communists, which will be major Communist
                            victory.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>We urge <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> be faced with
                            choice of (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) presenting united front at
                            conference which fully protects his and <gloss target="#t_ROK1"
                                >ROK</gloss> position and which will result in Communists bearing
                            responsibility for failure conference; or (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>)
                            isolate <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> from allies which will
                            result in relieving Communists of onus for failure of conference. We
                            would, of course, in fact do maximum here avoid such a situation
                            (although we should not tell <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>
                            this) by attempting obtain all possible support for maintaining present
                            situation in which issues are primarily Communist failure accept <gloss
                                target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> role and proportional voice of North
                            Korea population, and if possible bring about break-up of conference on
                            these issues.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
